#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=17&annotation=DXHHJUUG][Page 17]]) Logical fallacies can make discussions and debates unproductive at best and impossible at worst. They are defined as "[misconceptions] resulting from a flaw in reasoning, or a trick or illusion in thoughts that often succeeds in obfuscating facts/truth" (Logical Fallacies 2022).
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=18&annotation=MSX5MJ66][Page 18]]) An appeal to nature is an argument that relies on basing what is ethically/ morally "good" on what is commonly seen as "natural" and what is "bad" on what is "unnatural." In this form, the use and consumption of nonhuman animals by humans are automatically "good," "natural," and "acceptable" because humans (or other animals like lions) have done it historically.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=18&annotation=WHBYKXPG][Page 18]]) For example, as Leftists, none of us would argue that murder, violation, oppression, discrimination, violence, or domination would be currently acceptable just because human history (and, in some instances, throughout the animal kingdom) is littered with examples.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=20&annotation=CTMMWAPP][Page 20]]) Likewise, whether the early consumption of nonhuman animals aided in human brain size evolution or not has no bearing on how we should behave now.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=21&annotation=4MFYZWDT][Page 21]]) Thought-terminating clich√©s ‚Ä¢ "Eating animals is a personal choice." ‚Ä¢ "Morality is subjective." ‚Ä¢ "To each their own." ‚Ä¢ "Live and let live." ‚Ä¢ "Agree to disagree." Phrases such as these are a type of rhetoric, which R.J. Lifton (2014) describes as when '[t]he most far-reaching and complex of human problems are compressed into brief, highly reductive, definitivesounding phrases, easily memorized, and easily expressed.‚Äù As Malone (2021:4-5) explains, these statements "aim to stop any further inquiry, development, or criticism of the thought. [Users of this fallacy] want to use the phrase and for that to be an end to the conversation before it can even begin."
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=22&annotation=QT2GJQER][Page 22]]) There are your "personal choices," but there are also their personal choices; and their personal choices are, in every respect, being omitted from the equation.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=22&annotation=UXKIQ8W4][Page 22]]) Tu quoque fallacy ‚Ä¢ "Vegans kill animals, too." ‚Ä¢ "Vegans also have blood on their hands." ‚Ä¢ "Factory farming is bad, but vegans harm human farm workers." This argument relies exclusively on pointing to assumed hypocrisy in vegans or veganism. Called a tu quoque fallacy (pronounced ‚Äútoo qw≈ç-qwƒì)---or an appeal to hypocrisy---the main topic of the discussion is typically derailed so that the vegan advocate must defend their own behaviors.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=23&annotation=RV67XD6D][Page 23]]) Red herring A vegan says, "Harming other animals is wrong," and someone else responds with: ‚Ä¢ "What about plants, though?" ‚Ä¢ "What about Indigenous rights, though?" ‚Ä¢ ‚ÄúWhat about humane meat, though? This fallacy, intentionally or unintentionally, derails from the original topic
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=23&annotation=UVHM5Z4N][Page 23]]) Perfect solution fallacy / nirvana fallacy ‚Ä¢ "No one is 100% vegan." ‚Ä¢ "Veganism won't solve all the world's problems." Unfortunately, there are no easy solutions to complex issues like human and nonhuman animal exploitation. The perfect solution fallacy---also known as the nirvana fallacy---rejects a proposed solution as not fully fixing a problem
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=26&annotation=HF7ELBXI][Page 26]]) Sentience is concerned with the ability to experience positive and negative experiences (or "any | 26 | feelings"), while consciousness is having an inner life or mind (Jablonka and Ginsburg 2022:402).
#+end_quote

