#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=43&annotation=J59HQHAL][Page 43]]) de Waal goes on to ask the obvious question if we are so concerned about anthropomorphism: shouldn't we also care about underestimating nonhuman animal cognitive abilities and overestimating human complexities?
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=43&annotation=2EGGC2AR][Page 43]]) As Fran√ßois Jaquet (2021:6) explains, speciesism probably developed (at least in part) from tribalism
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=43&annotation=L3SFQA8L][Page 43]]) And while tribalism has evolved throughout history and could have led to speciesism, there is the possibility that "speciesist beliefs are shaped by evolution. If evolution is disconnected from ethical truth, this means that [these speciesist beliefs] are unjustified" (12).
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=43&annotation=EA5S3UH3][Page 43]]) If we were to gauge these evolutionary social categorizations of others as "normal," "natural," or "good," we would also be forced to see evolutionary ethical truth in other forms of discrimination (12).
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=44&annotation=MRARFUZ8][Page 44]]) As human groups began to be less nomadic and more sedentary, the domestication of nonhuman animals and plants began. Because of domestication, social hierarchies between and within human groups became more pronounced.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=44&annotation=MEC6SIA6][Page 44]]) Specifically, control over more nonhuman animals became a status signifier. And while human groups were being more clearly differentiated socially, the environment and nonhuman animals were beginning to become more heavily exploited and became "resources" for humans because doing so could elevate one's status.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=44&annotation=HCRB4IXH][Page 44]]) These two states of change---egalitarianism to social hierarchy and the domestication of nonhuman animals and nature into "resources"---created, as Maurizi describes it, a "feedback" loop.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=45&annotation=3GMK6TQP][Page 45]]) Add to this the shift from animist religions to anthropocentric religions, whereby deities are no longer other animals but rather those humans higher on the social hierarchy; nonhuman animals became something to disparage and equate to lowerstatus humans.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=45&annotation=EIQ3FLD4][Page 45]]) Nonhuman animals and humans lower in the social hierarchy became materially exploitable; thus, the ideologies involved in speciesism and human oppressions became aids in this exploitation---albeit historically later than the material form.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=45&annotation=6HB9PIHF][Page 45]]) Nonhuman animal and human oppressions co-constitute one another, as "without animal exploitation there is no class society, but without class society there is no speciesism"
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=46&annotation=68PDL339][Page 46]]) not only do we see JOHN TALLENT | 46 | humans as an "in-group" and nonhuman animals as an "out-group," but we also see other animals like dogs as a type of "in-group" that is separate and "superior" to the other nonhuman animals like pigs that we consider "inferior."
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=48&annotation=MSBPM7UW][Page 48]]) SD-HARM has also been shown to connect speciesism and sexism. Five studies published in a report by Gra√ßa et al. (2018) showed that higher speciesist attitudes correlated to being more likely to dehumanize women and consider them as "more closely related to nature," a form of benevolent sexism16.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=48&annotation=DPRZ44LA][Page 48]]) Ideas of masculinity and femininity and the degree to which one holds human supremacist values can affect the probability that someone will consume nonhuman animals (Weber and Kollmayer 2022).
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=49&annotation=ZUGYIJCF][Page 49]]) Loughnan, Haslam, and Bastian (2010:158) put forth evidence that the practice of eating nonhuman animals "leads people to withdraw moral concern from both animals in general and the animal they ate."
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=49&annotation=GW3P8X42][Page 49]]) the researchers found that eating nonhuman animals' bodies "indirectly leads people to deny the animal they ate the mental states closely linked to the capacity to suffer."
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=50&annotation=YSQAUZPK][Page 50]]) The specific form of cognitive dissonance around the meat paradox has been termed "meat-related cognitive dissonance" or "MRCD" (Rothgerber 2019).
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=50&annotation=AK3IRQA2][Page 50]]) five main tactics to prevent the psychological discomfort that MRCD creates: avoidance, willful ignorance, dissociation, perceived behavioral change, and do-gooder derogation
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=51&annotation=GZSDARM9][Page 51]]) Changing peoples' opinions, beliefs, and behaviors can be extremely dif√ècult. Attempts at interventions designed to alter peoples' harmful behaviors suggest that simple "debunkings" of original views can result in a boomerang effect:
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=52&annotation=YJYSIBK5][Page 52]]) when people feel that others judge them morally about their behaviors and actions, they feel resentment.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=52&annotation=N2WE3I38][Page 52]]) non-vegans frequently only follow other non-vegans' recommendations to cut back on or to stop consuming nonhuman animals because they dislike vegans and vegetarians.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=52&annotation=AQE2KCQA][Page 52]]) This has been explained as an intergroup sensitivity effect, whereby those identifying as "meat-eaters" trust more in those identifying the same way
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=53&annotation=SY8TBH2U][Page 53]]) Feeling judged can be valid, but we must remember that feelings of judgment can also be the work of our confirmation biases against vegans and vegetarians.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=53&annotation=IIPB3I9F][Page 53]]) The social psychologist Melanie Joy (2011:96-7) refers to the three most common explanations people use to defend their nonhuman animal consumption as the "Three Ns of Justification": that it is believed to be normal, natural, and necessary.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=53&annotation=R5WEVNXS][Page 53]]) Piazza et al. (2015) provide some of the earliest systematic evidence for this phenomenon in six studies, and they increase the Three Ns to include a fourth N: nice. They explain that the inclusion of "nice" into this list of common justifications involves the "[a]ppeals to the tastiness of meat, or that it is fulfilling or satisfying" (116).
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=54&annotation=2WWQ52S5][Page 54]]) Valuing humans over nonhuman animals, or even some nonhuman animals over other nonhuman animals, is mainly due to determining someone's moral status based on their cognitive abilities; in other words, anthropocentrism and speciesism are strongly connected to ableism.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=54&annotation=JS57KHKJ][Page 54]]) the authors of this research argue that mental capacities are not the only determinants of anthropocentric thinking---nonhuman animals simply being categorized as different species than humans is also a decisive factor.
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=54&annotation=BKG52IBB][Page 54]]) According to recent research, children exhibit less speciesism than young adults and older adults (McGuire, Palmer, and Faber 2022; Neldner and Wilks 2022)
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=55&annotation=NASF6R3N][Page 55]]) And because veg*ans are seen as going against societal norms, they become a human outgroup
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
