#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=82&annotation=A3GSV9XA][Page 82]]) "Compassionate conservation" (CC) is a perspective aimed at minimizing harm and suffering of all nonhuman animals, rejecting the widespread ideas that human supremacy and human exceptionalism are more important than individual nonhuman animal lives and autonomy, and seeking alternatives to killing as much as possible (Ramp and Bekoff 2015; Wallach et al. 2018). #D√©finitions
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=82&annotation=YMELS67B][Page 82]]) "multispecies justice" (MJ), is also gaining support within the area of conservation. Based upon the ethic of justice, it sees specific duties toward nonhuman animals. The obligatory nature of these duties is founded in the science of nonhuman animal cognition and sentience, where consciousness necessitates specific duties to safeguard a being's life and prevent undue pain and suffering when possible. #D√©finitions
#+end_quote

#+begin_quote
[!quote]+ Highlight ([[zotero://open-pdf/library/items/WP66FEUA?page=83&annotation=KXQHFE53][Page 83]]) "Nativism" in conservation describes the prevailing view that life native to a given area should be valued morally. In contrast, non-native life is valued less or not valued at all, morally speaking (Wallach et al. 2018). #D√©finitions
